article.description: Chamique Holdsclaw had 26 points, 13 rebounds and five steals Thursday night to lead the Washington Mystics to their first playoff victory in franchise history, a 74-62 win over the Charlotte Sting in Game 1 of the WNBA's Eastern Conference semifinals.

article.linkText: One-woman show: Mystics' Holdsclaw overwhelms Sting
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- For Chamique Holdsclaw, it's been a long time coming.
Thursday, Aug. 15
Chamique Holdsclaw was unstoppable, scoring 26 points on 9-for-18 shooting and tallying 13 rebounds and five steals.

She's a very difficult matchup for opponents, and can dominate at the 3, 4 or 5 positions. Holdsclaw, who has 13 double-doubles on the season, just has so many ways to attack you. She can take you baseline, or if you're bigger and stronger, she can go around you or elevate over you.

While Holdsclaw was a big part of the Mystics' first playoff win, Charlotte didn't do what it needed, either. The 3-point shot has been the Sting's bread and butter all season, and Charlotte set records this summer for 3-point shooting accuracy and baskets made. The Sting were able to keep the game close in the first half, sinking seven 3-pointers before the break, but they sank only one 3-point basket in the second half. This is a team that lives and dies by the 3, and Thursday, the Sting died by it.

The Sting's Charlotte Smith also struggled. She typically gives Charlotte an extra scorer at the 4, but she scored only two points against Washington and failed to give the Sting the offensive balance they're used to.
Four years after she became the most hyped No. 1 draft choice in the WNBA, Holdsclaw finally has a playoff victory. Her 26 points, 13 rebounds and five steals helped the Washington Mystics defeat the Charlotte Sting 74-62 Thursday in Game 1 of the WNBA's Eastern Conference semifinals. It was also the first playoff win in the Mystics' five-year existence, ending a drought that seemed longer for veterans like Holdsclaw and Tausha Mills. Earlier Thursday, coach Marianne Stanley was awarded the league's coach of the year. "I feel so blessed, man,'' said Holdsclaw, flashing a broad smile. "Since I've been in Washington, it's been up and down. Tausha made a comment in the locker room just now -- 'Hey, first time we've had a coach of the year, and the coach is actually favored to come back next year.' It feels good just to have stability for once, and it's something that's just going to grow.'' Charlotte, seeded second in the East, will host Game 2 of the best-of-3 series on Saturday and Game 3, if necessary, on Monday. The Sting beat the Mystics in 67-57 Tuesday in Charlotte to gain homecourt advantage for the series. The victory broke a six-game home losing streak for the third-seeded Mystics, who had lost nine of 11 overall to end the season. The Sting had won four straight. "It's nice to see Mystics basketball again,'' Stanley said. "This is the way we were playing early in the year. We're a team that likes to set a fast tempo, and we finally got one.'' The Mystics, who finished the regular season with a winning record (17-15) for the first time in their history, were swept in two games by New York in 2000 in their only other playoff appearance. Holdsclaw, who led the league in scoring and rebounding, was 9-for-18 from the field and 8-for-10 from the free-throw line. Coco Miller, honored before the game as the league's most improved player, added 12 points. Annie Burgess had eight assists. Andrea Stinson scored 16 points, and Allison Feaster had 15 to lead the Sting, who missed nine of their first 11 shots. "That set the tone, along with 14,000 people,'' coach Anne Donovan said. "It's tough when you're on the road to get in that kind of hole and then come back and make a game of it.'' Charlotte rallied in the first half with 3-pointers, making 7 of 16 in the first half. But the Sting were just 1-of-13 in the second half. Feaster's 3-pointer cut Washington's lead to 54-51 with 12:25 to play, but a four-point sequence by the Mystics' Tonya Washington stopped Charlotte's momentum. After Holdsclaw missed badly with a 3-pointer, Washington grabbed the rebound and was fouled. After she made both free throws, she intercepted a pass in the backcourt and made a layup to put the Mystics ahead 58-51. The Sting narrowed the deficit down to four twice more, but they could no longer hit from long range. Dawn Staley missed two 3s that would have cut the lead to a point near the five-minute mark. Holdsclaw was just 4-for-17 in the game at Charlotte on Tuesday. When she asked Stanley for advice, the coach said: "Stop floating.'' "Sometimes I settle,'' Holdsclaw said. "I let people push me away, but now I just have to put my body into it.'' Said Donovan: "She did not get a double-double in Charlotte, so we knew she was going to come out extra-motivated. She is the person that's going to carry the team to the next round.''
